03564nam a22004815i 9780804767385DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047673857 a10.1515/97808047673852doi  a(DE-B1597)581301  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aVA653b.S38 2005 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a322/.5/0952090341 aSchencking, J. Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Waves :bPolitics, Propaganda, and the Emergence of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1868-1922 /cJ. Charles Schencking. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b5 tables, 4 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tIntroduction -- t1 Maritime Dreams, Meiji Realities, 1868–1878 -- t2 Parochialism and Empire -- t3 Political Baptism by Fire -- t4 The Rich Rewards and Rivalry of War, 1894–1904 -- t5 War, Pageantry, and Propaganda in the Service of Naval Expansion, 1905–1910 -- t6 Coercion, Pragmatism, and Interservice Rivalry -- t7 The Rise and Fall of Navy Political Fortunes, 1913–1914 -- t8 Opportunism, Expansion and Limitation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores the political emergence of the Imperial Japanese Navy between 1868 and 1922. It fundamentally challenges the popular notion that the navy was a 'silent,' apolitical service. Politics, particularly budgetary politics, became the primary domestic focus—if not the overriding preoccupation—of Japan's admirals in the prewar period. This study convincingly demonstrates that as the Japanese polity broadened after 1890, navy leaders expanded their political activities to secure appropriations commensurate with the creation of a world-class blue-water fleet. The navy's sophisticated political efforts included lobbying oligarchs, coercing cabinet ministers, forging alliances with political parties, occupying overseas territories, conducting well-orchestrated naval pageants, and launching spirited propaganda campaigns. These efforts succeeded: by 1921 naval expenditures equaled nearly 32 percent of the country's total budget, making Japan the world's third-largest maritime power. The navy, as this book details, made waves at sea and on shore, and in doing so significantly altered the state, society, politics, and empire in prewar Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 4aHistory -- World. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476738540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767385/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles